 © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Sheffield (Yorkshire), but perhaps also from Sheffield Bottom in Burghfield (Berkshire), or Sheffield Park in Fletching (Sussex). The Yorkshire place takes its name from the river Sheaf, itself from Old English <i>scēath</i> ‘boundary’, + Old English <i>feld</i> ‘open country’, while the Berkshire placename derives from Old English <i>scēo</i> ‘shelter’ + <i>feld</i>. The Sussex placename comes from Old English <i>scēap</i> ‘sheep’ + <i>feld</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Shuffield","meanings":["English: variant of   Sheffield  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":63,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Sheffield II was born in 1196, in Leicestershire, England, his father, Sir Robert de Sheffield Knight Templar, was 31 and his mother, Felicia de Terneby, was 26. He had at least 5 sons with Agnes or Anne Gower or Goure. He died in 1270, in Hemswell, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1196–1270":"1196–1270","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1240–1311":"1240–1311","1250–1312":"1250–1312","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1312":"1312","1311":"1311","1166":"1166","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Hemswell, Lincolnshire, England":"Hemswell, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1196–1270":"1196–1270","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1240–1311":"1240–1311","1250–1312":"1250–1312","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","1264–Male":"1264–Kuollut","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1312":"1312","1311":"1311","1166":"1166","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Hemswell, Lincolnshire, England":"Hemswell, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1196–1270":"1196–1270","1220–Female":"1220–Décédée","1240–1311":"1240–1311","1250–1312":"1250–1312","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","1262–Male":"1262–Décédé","1264–Male":"1264–Décédé","1166–Male":"1166–Décédé","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1262":"1262